// CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved

const data = {
  metaTitle: 'Corporate Training & Compliance Platform — All Webbed Labs',
  metaDescription: 'How we helped a national retail chain replace PowerPoint-based in-person training with a purpose-built LMS — lifting compliance completion rates from 61% to 94%, eliminating 200 hours of monthly manager delivery time, and building an audit-ready record for FairWork inspections.',
  industry: 'Education',
  tags: ['React', 'Node.js', 'PostgreSQL', 'SCORM', 'Xero HRIS Integration'],
  title: 'Corporate Training & Compliance Platform',
  summary: 'A national retail chain with 500 staff across 42 stores had a mandatory compliance training problem: 61% completion, no verifiable records, and new product rollouts taking six weeks because trainers had to visit every store in person. We built them a platform that lifted completion to 94%, put rollout time at three days, and gave them a defensible record for FairWork.',
  heroImageDescription: 'Split view showing the learner-facing module player with a food safety compliance course alongside the manager compliance dashboard displaying completion rates by store across three states',

  clientOverview: 'A national retail chain headquartered in Melbourne, operating 42 stores across Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland, with approximately 500 employees — a mix of permanent staff and casual workers across store operations, warehouse and head office functions. The business has operated for more than a decade and had reached a scale where informal training practices were creating both operational and legal exposure.',
  clientSize: '500 employees, 42 stores across VIC, NSW and QLD',
  clientLocation: 'Melbourne, VIC (head office)',

  pullQuote: 'When the FairWork inspector asked for our training records, I had to tell her I\'d have them by the end of the week. Now I can pull a complete, auditable report for every employee in under a minute. That\'s a very different conversation.',
  pullQuoteAuthor: 'Head of People & Culture',
  pullQuoteRole: 'National Retail Chain',

  challenge: [
    'Compliance training in a food retail environment is not optional. Food safety handling is mandated under Australia\'s Food Standards Code, and the standard requires not just that training happens but that records demonstrate it happened — who was trained, on what, when, and by whom. WorkHealth and Safety obligations under the relevant state WHS Acts require evidence of induction and ongoing safety training. The Fair Work Act 2009 creates exposure around anti-harassment and workplace rights training, not through a direct training mandate but through the way courts and the Fair Work Commission assess employer liability when complaints arise. The business knew it had obligations. The problem was that its current approach to meeting them was fragile.',
    'Training was delivered in person by store managers, working from PowerPoint decks emailed from head office. This approach had several compounding problems. First, managers varied significantly in how rigorously they delivered the content — some ran thorough sessions, others ran through slides quickly and ticked a completion box. Second, records were kept inconsistently: some stores maintained attendance sheets, others relied on a column in the staff roster spreadsheet, others had nothing at all. Third, when head office updated training content — a new food safety procedure, a change in WHS protocols following a near-miss incident, a product-specific handling requirement for a new range — distributing that change required someone at head office to email updated slides to 42 store managers, follow up with those who did not respond, and then wait while each manager found time to deliver the session in person.',
    'A new product range rollout had taken six weeks from head office sign-off to confirmed completion across all stores. During that window, the business had 42 stores theoretically operating with a product knowledge gap. From a customer experience perspective this created inconsistency; from a liability perspective — particularly for products with handling or safety requirements — it was a real risk. The six-week rollout time was not unusual; it was the norm.',
    'The 61% completion rate was identified through a manual audit that the head of People & Culture had commissioned after a near-miss incident at a Victorian store raised questions about whether the relevant safety training had been delivered. The audit took two weeks to complete, involved calling every store manager and requesting whatever records they had, and produced a figure that the leadership team found uncomfortable. Sixty-one percent meant that roughly one in three employees had no verifiable record of completing mandatory compliance training. In a FairWork or WorkSafe inspection context, that exposure was significant.',
    'There had been a near-miss with a FairWork inspection twelve months prior — not directly related to training records, but the experience of scrambling to locate documentation under time pressure had made the head of People & Culture determined to fix the underlying records problem before it became acute. The decision to invest in a platform was driven partly by efficiency and partly by genuine risk management.',
  ],

  whyUs: [
    'The business had looked at two well-known off-the-shelf LMS platforms. Both were capable products with good feature sets, but neither offered the specific integrations the business needed. The first had no connection to any HRIS or payroll system, meaning that staff records would need to be maintained manually in the LMS — a significant ongoing overhead in a retail business with high casual staff turnover. The second offered an integration but only with a small number of HR platforms, and not the Xero-based HRIS the business was already using.',
    'We were introduced through the business\'s IT consultant, who had worked with us on a separate internal systems project. What the head of People & Culture valued in our first conversation was that we asked about the FairWork and food safety regulatory context before we asked about features. We understood that the platform\'s most important output was not a completion percentage — it was a defensible, auditable record. That framing shaped everything from the data model to the reporting interface. We also proposed building SCORM-compatible content packaging from the beginning, which meant the business\'s existing compliance content — developed by a specialist training provider — could be imported without being rebuilt.',
  ],

  approach: [
    'We spent the first two weeks in discovery, working through the compliance landscape with the head of People & Culture and the company\'s external employment law adviser. We wanted to understand not just what training needed to be delivered, but what records needed to be kept, in what format, for how long, and for what purpose. The answer varied by module type: food safety records needed to align with the Food Standards Code\'s traceability expectations, WHS records had retention requirements under the relevant state regulations, and FairWork-relevant training needed to be traceable to individual employees with timestamps.',
    'We mapped out six training categories from the brief: food safety (mandatory for all food-handling staff), WHS induction (mandatory for all staff within the first week of employment), WHS refresher (annual, mandatory), anti-harassment and workplace rights (annual, mandatory), new product training (triggered on product launch, variable by role), and manager-specific modules (leadership responsibilities, first aid refresher, rostering compliance). Each category had different completion rules, different audience definitions, and different record-keeping requirements.',
    'The Xero HRIS integration was central to the design. Rather than asking the People & Culture team to maintain a separate staff list in the LMS, we proposed pulling the source of truth — the employee record in Xero — into the platform on a nightly sync. New employees appeared in the system automatically and were enrolled in their mandatory induction modules without any manual action from head office. Employees who left the business were marked inactive, retaining their training history for the legally required retention period but no longer appearing in active completion reports.',
    'We prototyped the reporting interface before building any of the course delivery functionality. The reports were the end product — the thing the business needed to be able to produce when required. Getting the report design right first meant we could work backwards to ensure the data model captured everything the reports needed. We walked the head of People & Culture through three proposed report formats and she selected one, making several adjustments. The final design showed completion status by module, by store, by role, and by individual employee, with date-stamped completion certificates downloadable as PDFs.',
  ],

  solution: [
    'The platform consists of two parts: a learner-facing module player and an administrative dashboard. The module player is the interface that store staff see — clean, mobile-optimised, and deliberately simple. Staff access it via a link on the in-store tablet or their own device, log in with their employee number and a PIN, and are presented with their assigned modules. Modules they have not yet started are flagged. Modules with upcoming deadlines are highlighted. Completed modules show their completion date and a link to their certificate.',
    'SCORM 1.2 was the content packaging standard we used for all modules. The business\'s existing compliance content had been developed by a specialist provider in SCORM-compatible format, which meant we could import existing modules into the new platform without rebuilding them. New modules created in-house are authored in a simple slide-based editor we built into the admin interface, which outputs SCORM packages automatically. The SCORM runtime handles the tracking of module completion, quiz scores and time-on-task, which feeds the audit records.',
    'Quiz completion is required for all compliance modules before a completion record is generated. Minimum pass scores are set per module — food safety modules require 80%, WHS modules require 75%. Staff who fail a quiz are shown which questions they answered incorrectly (without revealing the correct answer immediately) and can attempt the module again after a 24-hour cooling-off period. The platform tracks all attempts, not just the final completion, which is relevant for any investigation of whether adequate training was provided.',
    'Certificate generation uses a PDF template populated with the employee name, module name, completion date, quiz score and a unique verification code. Certificates are stored in S3 and accessible to the employee at any time through their training history. For the business\'s purposes, the certificate is less important than the audit report — but for employees who have completed training, having a tangible record of their qualification has proved to be appreciated, particularly for food safety and first aid certifications that staff sometimes need to provide to other employers.',
    'The administrative dashboard gives head office a real-time view of compliance status across all stores and all modules. The default view is a traffic-light grid: stores in green have above-threshold completion for all active mandatory modules, stores in amber have one or more modules below threshold, stores in red have critically low completion or overdue mandatory enrolments. Store managers see only their own store. Area managers see their cluster. The People & Culture team sees everything. Role-based access means each level sees what they need without being overwhelmed by data for locations they are not responsible for.',
    'New product training is triggered through the admin interface. When head office creates a new product training module, they assign it to a role set (for example, all food handling staff) and set a completion deadline. The system enrols the relevant staff automatically — drawing on the Xero sync to know which employees hold that role — and sends them a push notification and email linking them directly to the module. Head office can watch completion percentages update in real time across all stores. The six-week rollout process has been replaced with a three-day average completion time for new product modules.',
    'The Xero HRIS integration runs as a nightly background job. It pulls the current employee list, compares it to the platform records, creates new staff accounts for new employees with their mandatory induction modules pre-enrolled and a welcome email triggered, marks departed employees as inactive, and updates role or location changes that might affect module enrolment. The People & Culture team described this as the most valuable single feature of the platform — the manual overhead of maintaining a separate staff list had been a recurring source of both errors and frustration.',
  ],

  implementation: [
    'The rollout sequence was designed to give head office confidence before deploying to stores. We spent the first month working with the People & Culture team and a pilot group of four stores — one in each metro area and one regional. The pilot group completed their induction modules on the new platform while still receiving traditional training as backup. This generated real usage data on mobile device compatibility, session length, and drop-off points within modules, which led to several UX adjustments before the broader rollout.',
    'Store manager training was conducted via a video call session, not in person. Managers were sent a short guide in advance, joined a 45-minute call in groups of six, and were walked through the manager-facing features of the dashboard. Most found it straightforward. The few who had questions after the call contacted a dedicated support email address that the People & Culture team monitored, with our team copied in for technical queries.',
    'The full 42-store rollout happened over a three-week period. We staggered activation by state — Victorian stores first, then New South Wales, then Queensland — which meant any issues identified in the first cohort could be addressed before the next group went live. The main issue that emerged was that some stores\' in-store tablets did not support the video playback for certain module formats; we added a fallback audio-narrated slideshow option for those devices within a week of identifying the issue.',
    'Data migration — specifically, importing historical completion records from the various spreadsheets and attendance sheets that existed across stores — was a deliberate decision point. We assessed the quality of the historical data and concluded that importing it would create more problems than it solved: formats were inconsistent, dates were sometimes approximate, and some records were missing employee identifiers. We advised the business to treat the platform launch as a clean baseline and to document this decision formally, so that if historical compliance was ever questioned, there was a clear explanation of why pre-platform records were stored separately rather than integrated.',
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    'We underestimated the variation in how staff would access the platform. Our assumption going in was that most staff would use in-store tablets during shift downtime. In practice, a significant number of staff — particularly casuals — preferred to complete training on their own mobile devices at home, sometimes outside of work hours. This was operationally positive for the business but required us to make the mobile experience more robust than our initial designs had assumed. Session resumption across device changes, in particular, needed to be more reliable than our first implementation.',
    'The SCORM standard, while useful for content portability, was more limited than we expected when it came to capturing the granular completion data the business needed for its FairWork compliance records. SCORM 1.2 reports completion status and a quiz score, but does not natively capture the data we wanted for audit purposes — individual question-level responses, time stamps per question, retry attempts. We supplemented the SCORM runtime data with our own event logging layer, which captures this information independently. The lesson: when compliance record-keeping requirements are specific, do not rely solely on the content packaging standard to meet them.',
    'The anti-harassment and workplace rights module required more iteration than any other content area. This was not a technical problem — it was a content problem. The initial module, developed by the training provider, included scenario-based questions that several staff and one area manager found ambiguous in their correct answers. The People & Culture team requested changes to three questions before the module was deployed broadly. We should have built a more formal content review and approval step into the implementation process for sensitive modules rather than treating content review as a pre-deployment task we assumed had already happened.',
    'Casual staff turnover proved to be higher than the Xero sync frequency could comfortably handle for induction training. In peak retail periods, a store might onboard three new casual staff in a single day — and the nightly sync meant those staff could go a full day without their induction modules being available. We addressed this with a manual "trigger sync" button for the People & Culture team, which proved sufficient. A real-time webhook from Xero would be cleaner, but Xero\'s API at the tier the business was on did not support employee webhooks at the time of build.',
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    'Following the first full year of operation, the business asked us to add a manager coaching module — a more conversational format that pairs store managers with self-directed scenarios and reflection prompts rather than didactic content. This was a different content format from the compliance modules and required building a new module type in the platform\'s content authoring tools.',
    'The business is now exploring using the platform for customer service and sales training — extending beyond mandatory compliance to development training. This was always a possible future direction, but the People & Culture team wisely wanted the compliance foundation solid before expanding scope. The underlying platform architecture supports this without modification; it\'s primarily a content and audience configuration exercise.',
    'The success of the platform was also the catalyst for a broader HR systems review. Having reliable, integrated training records for the first time surfaced how much other people-data was still living in spreadsheets. We have been engaged to scope a more comprehensive people dashboard that would connect training completion, performance review cycles and rostering data in a single view for area managers.',
  ],

  resultsNarrative: 'The compliance completion rate moving from 61% to 94% is the headline number, but what it represents is more significant than the percentage suggests. It means the business can now answer the question "has every food-handling staff member completed their food safety training?" with yes — and can prove it with a date-stamped, named record for every employee. Before the platform, that question had no reliable answer. The FairWork and food safety regulatory context makes that shift from unknown to known genuinely material.',

  metrics: [
    { value: '94%', label: 'Compliance training completion rate', context: 'Up from 61% under the previous in-person delivery model; measured across all mandatory modules' },
    { value: '3 days', label: 'New product training rollout time', context: 'Down from six weeks of store-by-store in-person delivery' },
    { value: '500', label: 'Staff with verified training records', context: 'First time the business had a complete, auditable record for every employee across all 42 stores' },
    { value: '~200 hrs/mo', label: 'Manager training delivery time eliminated', context: 'Estimated aggregate across 42 store managers who previously delivered in-person sessions' },
    { value: '$2.40', label: 'Platform cost per completion', context: 'Versus approximately $18.50 per completion for in-person delivery (including manager time and travel)' },
    { value: '<1 min', label: 'FairWork audit report generation', context: 'Full compliance record for any employee, any module, exportable as PDF with digital signatures' },
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: 'React', reason: 'Learner-facing module player and admin dashboard with complex role-based views and real-time completion tracking' },
    { name: 'Node.js', reason: 'Backend API, background sync jobs, and SCORM runtime event processing' },
    { name: 'PostgreSQL', reason: 'Relational structure for the complex enrolment, completion and audit record requirements' },
    { name: 'SCORM 1.2', reason: 'Industry-standard content packaging enabling import of externally developed compliance modules' },
    { name: 'AWS (EC2 + RDS + S3 + CloudFront)', reason: 'Sydney-region hosting; CloudFront for video content delivery to stores; S3 for certificate PDF storage' },
    { name: 'Xero HRIS Integration', reason: 'Nightly employee sync eliminating the need to maintain a separate staff list; automatic enrolment on new hire' },
    { name: 'PDF Certificate Generation', reason: 'Date-stamped completion certificates with verification codes, stored in S3 and linked to employee records' },
    { name: 'Push Notifications (Web Push)', reason: 'Module assignment alerts sent to staff devices without requiring a native app install' },
  ],

